    "body": "@thomas-huet I'm not sure: I believe the implementations agree with the yellow paper. For example in `aleth`:\r\n```\r\nm_SPP[0] = m_SP[0] < 32 ? (m_SP[1] >> (unsigned)(8 * (31 - m_SP[0]))) & 0xff : 0;\r\n```\r\nso if the first stack argument is 0, the second stack argument is shifted right by 248 bits (and the last byte masked). This gives the most significant bit, not the least.\r\n\r\nAlso worth comparing with KEVM, see the definition of `BYTE` [here](https://github.com/kframework/evm-semantics/blob/e2f6dffa3cf861a7d9b23a8699dc97f1cae97e7d/evm.md#expressions) and the definition of `byte(N, W)` [here](https://github.com/kframework/evm-semantics/blob/master/data.md#bitwise-operators). It is likewise counting starting with the MSB.",
